<text top=""55"" left=""159"" width=""608"" height=""27"" font=""0"">Wilkes University Career Services Resume Guide </text>
<text top=""107"" left=""135"" width=""645"" height=""14"" font=""2"">A resume documents one's qualifications for a position. It is your marketing tool and its main purpose is to </text>
<text top=""124"" left=""135"" width=""636"" height=""14"" font=""2"">help you get an interview. Your accomplishments and qualifications should be presented in an interesting </text>
<text top=""141"" left=""135"" width=""607"" height=""14"" font=""2"">and efficient manner, as they relate to a career or position. A resume is a summary of one's personal, </text>
<text top=""158"" left=""135"" width=""548"" height=""14"" font=""2"">educational, and work experience and qualifications; it need not be a complete life history. </text>
<text top=""193"" left=""135"" width=""628"" height=""14"" font=""2"">While it is true that there is no one correct way to design a resume, there are certain traditions in resume </text>
<text top=""210"" left=""135"" width=""647"" height=""14"" font=""2"">writing that have become standard. The descriptions which follow are intended to help you create a resume </text>
<text top=""227"" left=""135"" width=""492"" height=""14"" font=""2"">that will serve your individual needs and represent your individual qualifications. </text>
<text top=""279"" left=""135"" width=""637"" height=""14"" font=""2"">Your resume should be neatly printed and be free of typo’s and errors. Typically a resume should be only </text>
<text top=""296"" left=""135"" width=""578"" height=""14"" font=""2"">one page long. There are individual exceptions however. If you have a large number of relevant </text>
<text top=""314"" left=""135"" width=""634"" height=""14"" font=""2"">experiences to offer, a two page resume may be necessary. Make sure your most important qualifications </text>
<text top=""331"" left=""135"" width=""629"" height=""14"" font=""2"">are mentioned on the first page and the information should fill at least one half of the second page. Your </text>
<text top=""348"" left=""135"" width=""610"" height=""14"" font=""2"">resume should be printed on good quality paper; grey, crème or white, no larger than 8 ½ x 11. Use a </text>
<text top=""365"" left=""135"" width=""618"" height=""14"" font=""2"">standard business font such as Ariel or Times Roman, with font no larger than 12, no smaller than 10.  </text>
Margins should be well balanced. Avoid using Microsoft resume templates, they often omit critical
<text top=""400"" left=""135"" width=""637"" height=""14"" font=""2"">information, are very difficult to edit and often do not retain the original format when e-mailed.  Just start </text>
<text top=""417"" left=""135"" width=""633"" height=""14"" font=""2"">with a blank word document. Do not include your age, birth date, social security number, weight, height, </text>
<text top=""434"" left=""135"" width=""621"" height=""14"" font=""2"">hobbies or other personal information. Keep everything professionally related.  Avoid excessive use of </text>
<text top=""452"" left=""135"" width=""199"" height=""14"" font=""2"">bolding, underlining and italics.  </text>
Begin your resume with your CONTACT INFORMATION. This should be centered at the top of the
<text top=""503"" left=""135"" width=""595"" height=""14"" font=""2"">page and should include your name, address, phone number and, e-mail. If you have a campus and </text>
<text top=""521"" left=""135"" width=""640"" height=""14"" font=""2"">permanent home address, include them both if appropriate for your situation.  Be sure your e-mail address </text>
<text top=""538"" left=""135"" width=""641"" height=""14"" font=""2"">is professional sounding, preferably just your name @ whatever.com. Avoid using any silly or offensive e-</text>
<text top=""555"" left=""135"" width=""245"" height=""14"" font=""2"">mail addresses you may use for friends.  </text>
Susie College
<text top=""607"" left=""420"" width=""82"" height=""14"" font=""2"">123 Main St. </text>
<text top=""624"" left=""386"" width=""149"" height=""14"" font=""2"">Wilkes-Barre PA 18702 </text>
Next comes your OBJECTIVE. An objective is a brief statement that communicates to an employer what
<text top=""728"" left=""135"" width=""585"" height=""14"" font=""2"">type of job you are seeking. Avoid the use of pronouns such as “I” and “me”. Avoid flowery and </text>
<text top=""745"" left=""135"" width=""599"" height=""14"" font=""2"">philosophical objectives, keep them specific and to the point. You may hear that an objective is not </text>
<text top=""762"" left=""135"" width=""620"" height=""14"" font=""2"">necessary. Research shows that employers view resumes without an objective as unfocused and weak.  </text>
Bad Objective Example: A career with a progressive organization where I can use my education, skills,
abilities and experience to effectively contribute to the overall organization.
<text top=""848"" left=""135"" width=""636"" height=""14"" font=""2"">What kind of job does this person want? An employer reading this would have no idea what this person’s </text>
<text top=""866"" left=""135"" width=""639"" height=""14"" font=""2"">career goals are. The person reading your resume wants to know what you can contribute to the company. </text>
<text top=""883"" left=""135"" width=""494"" height=""14"" font=""2"">What’s in it for them? Match the organizations’ needs to your skills and abilities.  </text>
Good Objective Examples: A mechanical engineering position in manufacturing operations and
development where mechanical aptitude and commitment to safety can contribute to profits and efficiency.
A position as an auditor with a large public accounting firm.
<text top=""1004"" left=""135"" width=""631"" height=""14"" font=""2"">An objective can limit your options if it is too specific. That's why it's a good idea to write a new one for </text>
<text top=""1021"" left=""135"" width=""639"" height=""14"" font=""2"">each position you apply for. Always tailor it for the job you seek. If there is no specific job advertised and </text>
<text top=""1038"" left=""135"" width=""603"" height=""14"" font=""2"">you are applying for possible openings in an organization of interest, mention the qualifications you </text>
<text top=""1055"" left=""135"" width=""313"" height=""14"" font=""2"">possess as they relate to the organizations’ mission: </text>
EXAMPLE: To contribute my education and experience in the social services to assist mental health
